nol production nor did they imagine that corn prices would reach all time highs at $8 per bushel $275 per metric ton that july futures prices for corn in chicago would exceed those for wheat that the united states would be exporting ethanol to brazil or that an iowa senator would co sponsor a bill to reduce corn based subsidies just prior to the iowa caucuses for the 2012 primary season what has caused these extraordinary circumstances and what are the economic political and food security implications of a revolution in demand that has caught both economists and political leaders unaware download html+ go to site external http www the american interest co parent research biofuels expansion implications for global food markets land use change and climate topics energy food security global food markets brazil united states search fsi search within everything courses events fellowships news op eds people publications research other pages publication news us ethanol policy major contributor to global food price volatility october 11 2011 fse fsi stanford news publications of interest sugar and ethanol production as a rural development strategy in brazil evidence from the state of sao paulo luiz martinelli rachael garrett silvio ferraz rosamond l naylor agricultural systems vol 104 5 2011 html+ cover greater transportation energy and ghg offsets from bioelectricity than ethanol j elliot campbell david lobell christopher field science 2009 html+ cover project timeline program for the study of biofuels poverty and food security jikun huang mark rosengrant scott rozelle rosamond naylor walter falcon david victor kenneth cassman 2007 pdf+ sustainable biofuels redux holly gibbs et al science vol 322 2008 html+ cover support map & directions contact rss+ rss xml feeds freeman spogli institute for international studies encina hall 616 serra st stanford ca 94305 6055 tel 650 723 4581 fax 650 725 2592 mail code 6055
